<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-790-694  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 790 694.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 27 1990 v24 n35 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>It's all Cyber systems go for Soviets. (Control Data Corp. andUSSR ready for mainframe sale)(Control Data Corp.'s Cyber 960mainframes)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Booker, Ellis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Control Data Corp received a license to export six Cyber 960mainframes to the Soviet Union thanks to a liberalization of theCoordinating Committee on Multilateral Export Controls (Cocom)rules.andP;  The systems will be paid for in hard currency and cost atotal of $32 million; three are to be delivered in 1990 and theother half in 1991.andP;  The Cyber 960s will be put to use analyzingsafety factors in power plants.andP;  The shipment is particularlysignificant because the Cyber 960 is the most powerful computersystem ever sold to the Soviets.andP;  In Aug 1990 the Soviet Union andUS made an agreement on mainframe usage safeguards.andP;  An agreementover the use of the Control Data Cyber 960's made in June by thetwo countries will dictate control of the computers.andP;  Certainsafeguards and on-site visits are defined in the agreement.andO;Control Data has also signed a technology sharing agreement withthe USSR's Academy of Sciences.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Control Data Corp. (export-import trade).andO;Ticker:    CDA.andO;Product:   Control Data Cyber 960 (Mainframe computer) (export-import trade).andO;Topic:     Soviet UnionMainframe computersInternational TradeCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsExport.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>